column168: A rolloff box containing hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  During check in, it was noticed that there was a small leak from the rear tailgate. After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, an absorbent material was placed on the affected areas to clean up the spill.  The material was placed back into the box.  The box sat in containment until being accepted into the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: Testing indicated approximately 5% free liquid at the bottom of the box.  The generator was notified that they needed to review their solification process to remove all liquids from the box before loading.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  Upon opening the rear door, to unload the trailer and reload the shipments into trailers destined for various disposal sites, a small amount of liquid was discovered on the trailer floor.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the dock personnel found that a small pinhole leak was in the bottom of a drum. The shipment was then loaded on a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver who picked up the shipment stated that there was no leak or signs of a hole at the time of pickup.  It is believed that the drum was corroded and that during the rigors of transportation, a sharp object on the pallet rubbed against the drum causing the leak.  The shipper was notified of the leak and cautioned against loading old corroded drums.

column168: Material handler was in process of loading drums of various waste chemicals onto Clean Harbors trailer# 6336 with a forklift at approximately 1610hrs. As he entered the trailer he noticed a small leak coming from the bottom area of one of the drums.  The operator shut down the forklift and exited the trailer. The leaking drum and the clean up materials were placed into a 85 gallon overpak drum. Area was secure at 1730hrs.

During transit a passing motorist indicated to our driver that there was a problem with his load.  He was able to pull over safely off the side of the road and discovered that an IBC had developed a vertical crack in the body and was leaking the tote contents.  The crack which developed was approximately 1.5-2 feet in length.  The driver called in the incident to corporate management and Highway Patrol arrived on the scene.  An emergency response company was called to clean up the spilled material.  The material (sodium hydroxide solution) was on the dirt shoulder of the road and did not enter any other medium.  Traffic was controlled on several lanes of the Highway to allow for safe cleanup of the material.  Cal Trans was called onto the scene by the Highway Patrol.  Material was cleaned up to the satisfaction of Cal Trans.  There were no injuries or additional incidents.
column169: This IBC was appropriate for the application and had passed all the testing and met requirements.  We are going to assess the use of this style of IBC to complete deliveries of hazardous material.

column168: PTRA was notified by FRA haz-mat Inspector Lambright at approximately 1030 hrs on November 8, 2012 that tank car UTLX 72818 was observed with product leaking from the manway area in the PTRA American Yard. After initial inspection by PTRA Director of Safety it was determined that the car could be moved over to the holding track in American Yard for repairs by M&M PRotection. The car was observed with product leaking from a defective vacuum relief valve on the manway cover. Product would only escape when the tank was moved during normal switching operations. Leakage was only noted on the left side of the tank car with no noticeable product on the ground.  The car was spotted in the holding track later that night and M&M Protection responded to the scene for repair and remediation the following morning 11/9/12. M&M removed the vaccuum relief valve and replaced the gasket and reinstalled the valce. The tank car was pressure washed with a biodegradeable micro bug solution and released from bad order status at 1230 hrs on November 9, 2012.
column169: ExxonMobil has been notified of the incident and is investigating to see if the vacuum relief valve was funtioning properly prior to loading and shipment from the refinery in Montana. The consignee, Tauber Oil, has also been made aware of the issues with the tank car.

column168: Narrative of incident for DOT Report     Sequence of events:  Cargo was loaded on the aircraft at Miami International Airport; there was no evidence of damaged or leaking Hazardous Materials packages per the preloading and after loading inspections by the Florida West Load Supervisor.   Approximately 20 minutes after takeoff the load supervisor entered the cargo compartment to perform an after takeoff check to verify the security of the load.  He could hear and see that there was gas escaping from one of the packages in the forward part of the cargo compartment (position 3R). The packages were still secure and in conformity with the orientation arrows. He left the compartment and shut the “smoke barrier” door.   A check of the NOTOC showed that there were 4 Dewars of UN1963 Helium, refrigerated liquid in that position.     Package failure details:  Unable to get any further details, Florida West procedures prohibit re-entry into the cargo compartment after a HazMat release has been detected. Upon Landing at Buenos Aires, crew was immediately transported to customs then to a hotel. The cargo was unloaded by LAN Cargo Airlines who had chartered our aircraft for this flight.    Duration of Leak:  Approximately 15 Minutes    Mitigating the effects:  Upon noticing the leak, the cargo compartment was isolated from the crew by securing the smoke barrier door. The ICAO ERG was consulted and complies with. The Captain called flight control for additional advice.    The Director of Safety called the 24 Hour Emergency Number on the Shipper’s Declaration, which was Chemtrec, Chemtrec transferred the call to the shipper, Praxair who located someone with knowledge of the product. They advise that the leaking container would be completely empty in 15 minutes or less and that if the cargo compartment remained isolated from the crew and vented overboard there was no danger to the occupants and no other measures needed to be taken during the flight. Per the shipper’s instructions, LAN Cargo was advised of the leak and advised to ventilate the aircraft before the unloading crew entering the cargo compartment.
column169: Do not have any recommendations regarding this event.

column168: A tanker trailer was being loaded with hazardous waste at the shipper's location.  When the trailer was approximately half loaded, the rear valve had fallen off the trailer and the material continued pumping until the driver shut off the valves with the emergency shutoff.  Approximately 50 gallons of liquid was spilled onto the concrete containment pad and into the drain into the sump where it recycles into the system.  A response crew was summoned both from the shipper and the transporter.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, all material was washed into the sump.  A mechanic replaced the valve on the trailer and it was disptached to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  TCEQ was notified--incident number 20123863.  The NRC was notified--incident number 1030638
column169: A weld on the clamp which holds the rear valve assembly onto the trailer had broken during the loading process.  The clamp and valve fell onto the ground as a result of this. column168: A BNSF yard crew reported a strong petroleum type odor emanating from standing railcars located near the middle of the railyard. A search of the location revealed tank car PPRX 55190 emanating the reported odor. PPRX 55190 was cordoned off awaiting arrival of summoned contract responders. Inspection of PPRX 55190 revealed its vapor valve was not fully closed and the vapor valve's closure plug was only hand tight. Responders closed the vapor valve and properly tool tightened its loose closure plug by 1450 hrs. CDT, 11/01/2012. Afterwards, the odor dissipated and responders monitored PPRX 55190 until no further odor was detectable. PROX 55190's valve housing cover's intact shipper seal A-839269 was replaced by seal numbered 652660.

column168: At approximately 1:20 AM, a loaded Sulfuric Acid tank car MDCX 1404 was found in train leaking from the top of the car. No exposure or contact was reported. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.    Once the responder arrived on-site and was briefed on situation, they conducted a tank car inspection. Upon further inspection of the tank car, it was discovered that the leak was generating from a loose fill tube lid. Also, it was noted that the fill tube gasket was misaligned. The responder replaced the misaligned gasket with a proper fitting gasket and the fill tube lid was tightened appropriately to tool tightness.    The leaked residue on the side and top of the tank car was nuetralized by means of Soda Ash. At approximately 4:52 AM, the tank car was secured and released back into transportation.    File Note Item 12-according to the waybill (Waybill #305492) the origin address differed from the shipping address. After diligent searching, the origin could not be verified by preparer of this report.    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases   (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On November 7, 2012, at 1744 hours, personnel in the CSXT Anderson yard discovered RACX 51956, a loaded tank car of Dicyclopentadiene, releasing vapors and odor from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Texmark Chemicals was notified via CHEMTREC report #2012-1107-00211. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two bolts on the liquid valve nozzle plate were less than tool tight and a plug into the nozzle plate had no sealant, releasing product. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Linda, 713-818-1920. Contractor personnel secured the bolts and rapped teflon tape around the plug and secured it. The car was decontaminated, the leak secured and released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI: 5(5+1+0)X(2+0)=   60  Cause Code: 662

column168: Vehicle 1, being a semi-tractor pulling a tanker, was traveling NB on St. Rt. 49. Vehicle 2, being a farm tractor pulling a grain wagon, was NB in front of Vehicle 1.  Vehicle 1 attempted to pass Vehicle 2.  Vehicle 1 and tanker was halfway past Vehicle 2 when Vehicle 2 turned left into the side of Vehicle 1.  Vehicle 2 was attempting to turn into a field.  Vehicle 2 lost front left dual tires. Tires went under the fitting box of the tank being pulled by Vehicle 1.  The tires acted as a ramp as Vehicle 1 continued NB and overturned.  Vehicle 1 tank trailer was gouged and began to leak onto roadway and in ditch line.  Emergency Responders at the scene were 3 fire departments (one being Mercer County) to contain product and spread sand around overturned unit.  Interdyne Corporation was called to handle emergency clean-up and remediation services.  Others that responded to scene were Mercer Co. Sheriffs Dept., Big Daddy's Towing, OH EPA, local highway department as well as other agencies not known.  We have not received descriptive reports that finalize remediation efforts at this point.
column169: Traveling the rural routes in agricultural areas require as much attention as the main interstate system.  We train our drivers to constantly be aware of their surroundings and, when approaching slower traffic, to take extra precautions such as following distances and clear passing lanes.  We will continue to train our drivers in this manner using this particular incident as a teaching opportunity.                                                                        The Safety Department has always felt that more training should be done concerning large vehicle awareness on a local level when persons apply for or renew a drivers license.  Enlist the help of trucking companies and insurance agencies (ones that provide trucking insurance) on a local level to achieve the training.

A rolloff box containing hazardous waste was being loaded onto the truck at the generator's site.  While pulling the box onto the rails with them in the air, the box was not on the rails properly and fell off the left side of the truck, landing on it's side.  The tarp held most of the material in the box, but approximately 10 pounds escaped onto the ground.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, uprighted the box and, using a backhoe, scooped the material and gravel back into the box.  The incident was reported to the Ohio EPA who assigned incident number 1211-02-2782.

column168: A vacuum tanker trailer was being loaded with waste crude oil from a frac tank.  The temperature at the time was below freezing and the oil was thick.  In order to speed up the process, the driver released a camlock fitting on the suction hose to allow some airflow to speed up the movement of the oil.  The other camlock then came loose and blew off the hose.  The valve on the frac tank was immediately closed however a couple of gallons of the material leaked onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled area.  2 shovelfuls of gravel were scooped up and placed into a drum which remained at the shipper's location.
column169: The operator did not follow proper standard operating procedures while loading the tanker.  When he returns to the office, he will be retrained in proper loading procedures.

column168: After loading a trailer containing various shipments of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility, the driver climbed on top of a 275 gallon tote in order to check his piece count.  The weight of the employee caused the metal support on top of the tote to break, piercing the tank.  A 16" crack resulted in approximately 1 cup of the waste material to leak on top of the tank and drip onto the trailer floor.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the spilled material was cleaned up with suitable absorbents and the damaged container was removed from the trailer and placed into containment where it was transferred into suitable salvage containers.

A shipment of hazardous waste was picked up and returned to intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into trailers being loaded for various intended waste disposal facilities.  When the trailer was being unloaded, a salvage drum was found to have a small leak.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the overpack drum into a suitable salvage container.  The small amount that had spilled onto the trailer floor was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material and placed into the drum.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drum was not leaking when it arrived at the truck transfer facility as the driver had performed his routine load check upon arrival.  The drum was a salvage drum containing a drum that had previously leaked.  Although it showed some signs of abrasion, the abrasion did not occur from the time of pickup to the time of arrival at the facility.  The shipper was notified of the incident.

column168: On November 17 2012 at the TRANSFLO-General Products transloading terminal in Charlotte, NC, a release of approximately 15 gallons of elevated temperature asphalt occurred. While in the process of unloading liquid asphalt from rail car UTLX 68985, it was discovered that a small stream of liquid asphalt was running out of the bleeder valve that is located on the unloading product hose. It was estimated that approximately 15 gallons of PG 64-22 asphalt was released from the bleeder valve on the product hose and hardened in the sand between the rails. The railcar is unloaded using a product hose that is connected to the bottom outlet of the railcar. This prodcut hose is connected after the asphalt is heated to a liquid state using steam. When the railcar is heated to the required temperature and the product hose is connected to the bottom railcar outlet, the valve on the railcar is opened which allows the asphalt to flow through the product hose.  Following the written procedure, the bleeder valve on the product hose is kept closed these steps. The employee responsible for the unloading stated that the bleeder valve on the product hose was in the closed position and that no leak was visible when the railcar valve was intially opened.  After a few minutes of unloading a stream of asphalt was released from the bleeder valve on the unloading product house. It is suspected that hardened asphalt in the bleeder valve of the product hose prevented the ball valve from seating fully when the hazmat employee closed the bleeder valve on that hose. As the asphalt flowed through the product hose, the hardened asphalt liquefied due to the heat and began to seep out of the bleeder valve. By the time that steam was removed from the railcar and the asphalt returned to a hardened state, approximately 15 gallons had released through the product hose bleeder valve. Fortunately all asphalt was contained within the sand between the two rails. Once the asphalt on the ballast hardened, it was shoveled out and disposed of.
column169: Corrective Actions to prevent reoccurance:   1) Replace the bleeder valve on the product hose- COMPLETED 11/9/2012  2) Instruct transloading hazmat employees to cycle the valve a few times to ensure all residual liquid asphalt is cleared from the bleeder valve. In addition the transloading hazmat employees should thoroughly inspect the product hose bleeder valve for signs that asphalt may have hardened in the valve.   3) Ensure the railcar valve is not opened if there is any difficultly closing the bleeder valve on the product hose- COMPLETED 11/9/2012   3) Re-train employees of the requirement to visually observe the product hose during the unloading process to ensure leaks do not occur when potentially hardened asphalt in the bleeder valve is liquefied. – COMPLETED -11/9/2012

column168: On November 15, 2012, acid from UN2794 batteries, wet, filled with acid was released from a battery due to a load shift on board an R&L Carriers tractor trailer. The release was due to a crack in the body of the battery and the acid impacted the cargo, trailer floor, and asphalt pavement. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to perform the necessary cleanup of the area. The contractor neutralized the released acid and applied absorbents to the impacted areas. Absorbents pads were utilized to wipe down the additional impacted areas on the trailer. The cargo was re-palletized and all waste was collected and containerized for proper transportation and disposal.

column168: On November 19, 2012, a Tennessee Commercial Warehouse tractor trailer containing totes of UN3266 Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Inorganic, n.o.s.(Sodium Hydroxide), rolled over, crushing two totes on board. Approximately 100 gallons of material was released to the trailer, roadway, and nearby soil as a result of this incident. No waterways or storm drains were impacted by the release. The local fire department and police department initially responded to the scene and closed the roadway and evacuated a nearby hotel. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to perform the proper remediation of the area. The contractor entered the trailer once up-righted to investigate the extent of the damage. The contractor contained the release with absorbents and applied absorbents to the impacted areas on the ground and in the trailer. A containment area of absorbents was built and the wrecker service lifted the trailer to drain the free standing product from the trailer onto the containment of absorbents. The contractor offloaded two damaged totes from the trailer but could not remove the remaining totes due to them being lodged inside because of the trailer being warped from the accident. The contractor transferred the contents of the damaged totes into drums for proper disposal. The site was secured and they returned at approximately 0900 EST on November 20, 2012, to excavate the impacted soils. ERTS has attempted to contact the local responding fire department and police department for information on the speed of the vehicle and amount of people evacuated, but has not been able to obtain this information. ERTS has also attempted to contacted the hotel for evacuation information, but the hotel was unwilling to provide any information to ERTS.

On November 2, 2012, Vitran Express contacted ERTS in regards to a release of a combustible liquid from a tote.  The tote was punctured by a forklift resulting in the release.  ERTS dispatched UST Environmental to the site to perform remediation activities.

column168: Tank car NATX 300080 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area during movement in the railyard.  Movement was stopped and inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed the leak source was at NATX 300080's 75 psi pressure relief valve (PRV) which is indicative of an overfilled condition. NATX 300080 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with containment (catch receptacle) placed under NATX 300080. Contract responders inspected NATX 300080 and confirmed that it was overfilled as only 3 inches of outage was observed  (standard 2% outage equates to almost 6 inches of outage).  The responder's reduced excess commodity using a vacuum truck and placed removed lading into the facility's used oil recovery tanks. The exterior of NATX 300080 was pressure washed of all spillage and the waste stream collected was placed into the facility's oil-water separator.  Intact shipper seals at the manway and valve housing cover were replaced by seals numbered 2877180 and 2877154 respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the appropriate commodity outages; and the total securement and the mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GAMX 6528 was reported leaking product from its manway closure in the railyard. GAMX 6528 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting contract responders' investigation and remediation. Responders found the manway securement bolts tool tight and manway closure shipper seals (numbered 329428 and 329429) intact. Further inspection for manway gasket condition revealed the manway gasket was missing as only a partial manway gasket piece (approximately six inches in length) was found in the gasketing location. Responders properly installed a new suitable manway nozzle gasket and tool tightened the manway securement bolts. New seals (numbered 2877200 and 2877199) were applied at the manway closure. The exterior of GAMX 6528 was pressure washed of all spillage and the waste stream collected was placed into the facility's oil-water separator.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On November 24, 2012 at approximately 10:30AM CDT a tractor-trailer operated by KLLM Transport Services, LLC was traveling northbound on I-81, when the driver was pulled over by Virginia State Police who noticed a leak coming from the front of the trailer. The driver exited the highway at exit 195 and parked on the shoulder of the road. A minimal amount of acrylic acid was leaking from the trailer floor to the asphalt surface of the highway.     The Virginia Department of Transportation, the Virginia Department of Emergency Management (VDEM) and the state hazmat team responded to the release to establish traffic control and perform the initial assessment of the release. State and county representatives also contacted Dow Chemical to gain insight as to the product released.      The responding agencies set up a command center and decon. facilities. The state hazmat team donned level A personal protective equipment (PPE) and entered the release area. Material leaking from outside the trailer froze due to the current weather conditions. Once the material thawed, soda ash was dispersed to neutralize the liquid. The crew entered the trailer and discovered two 55-gallon drums containing acrylic acid had fallen over during transport, and one had leaked releasing approximately 40 gallons to the trailer floor. The hazmat team used soda ash to collect and neutralize the freestanding fluid. The drum was flipped over and overpacked to prevent further release. Spent soda ash was left on the the trailer for transport to the destination facility.      Once the material had been cleaned, the Department of Transportation inspected the load and approved it for transport to its original destination. Hazmat crew members were deconned.

column168: While traveling south on US 69 in Beaumont, the driver was exiting Martin Luther King Dr. (MLK) to his left when he noticed product coming out of the drain tube on his trailer. He immediately pulled over to a safe location which was about 2 blocks from the intersection. By the time he pulled over, the Beaumont police/fire department were at the scene. They started their investigation and discovered that their was product spilled at 2 locations (at the intersection of US 69 and MLK and also at the spot our driver had pulled over). The estimated gals. spilled was about 10 gals. total. Once the spill was contained, they started their investigation to determine the cause of the spill. They discovered that there were 2 locations on the trailer that were leaking. The first leak was on the vapor line where it screws on to the trailer. The line was removed and repaired by installing a 3" cap in it's place. The 2nd leak was on the pressure relief valve. This leak was repaired by removing the leaking valve and replacing it with another valve.

column168: On November 27th at 0915, the stacker operator on the Horizon Lines San Juan, Puerto Rico contaianer yard was transiting the yard with the stacker spreader bar extended to the 40 foot wide position.  In manuvering a turn on the marine terminal, the driver of the stacker struck a loaded tank DCIU0750404 loaded with UN1648 Acetonnitrile class 3 toppling it from a third tier stack on to loaded tank DPCU001241-0 containing UN2478, Isocyanate Solution, Flammable, Toxic, NOS (Xylene Butylisocyanate)class 3(6.1).  The DCPU0001241-0 was damaged but there was no cargo leak.  A separate incident report will be filed to note this structural damage.    The fire department was notified immediately along with the Clean up Contractor, Clan Harbors and a report was made to Chemtrec along with the shipper.  A verbal report was filed with the NRC and the EQB in Puerto Rico.  The NRC Report noted communications with the EPA.  The spill was contained to the asphalt with oil dry berms.  No product entered any drains on the yard.  The USCG and the EQP were present during the clean up. The product from the leaking tank was transferred into another tank at the shipper's instructions.
column169: The stacker driver has had training on on top loaders and accident prevention.  He failed to retract the spreader to the twenty foot position when transiting the rows on the marine terminal.  The driver was placed on suspension.  The stacker drivers were again reminded of the risks when traversing the rows on the container yard.

column168: The facility had thirteen Intermediate Bulk Containers (IBCs) of off specification sodium hypochlorite solution.  We classified the material as Waste Hypochlorite Solutions, DOT Class 8, PG II, with a D002 waste code. On November 2nd, a Univar forklift operator was loading the IBCs into a trailer for shipment to the TSDF.  When loading the 12th of 13 IBCs, a fork, which extended beyond the back of the IBC, punctured a hole in the bottle of a previously loaded IBC, resulting in the release of sodium hypochlorite into the trailer.  The employee then picked up the damaged IBC and backed it out onto the concrete loading dock.  Additional plant employees used absorbent materials from the emergency spill kits in an attempt to contain the released material.  Some liquid ran beneath a dock door and outside to another concrete pad used for trailer loading.  Additionally, approximately 10 gallons of sodium hypochlorite was released from the trailer near the nose onto concrete and asphalt and pooled in soil surrounding railroad tracks.  Members of our technical support team used vacuums to recover free standing liquids.  The damaged IBC had contained approximately 300 gallons of liquids prior to the incident.  Approximately 50 gallons of liquid was recovered with the vacuums,  approximately 25 gallons remained in the tote and was not released.  We estimate that the absorbents recovered approximately 50 gallons.
column169: The forklift operator was retrained and recertified for forklift operation.    We will revise the local plant procedures for trailer loading/unloading.    Conduct refresher training for all plant employees on the use of spill tools, supplies and techniques.    Purchase additional spill containment equipment, including containment pools and stage throughput facility.

column168: AT 19:35 HRS DURING THE TWILIGHT SORT IN THE UPS SAN MARCOS FACILITY (A SMALLER UPS BUILDING), AN UNDAMAGED GROUND PACKAGE DISPLAYING THE MARKING "CHINESE AVIATION LITHIUM BATTERY COMPANY" WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR OF THE METRO UNLOAD AREA. THE PACKAGE BEGAN TO SMOKE, LEADING MANAGEMENT TO EVACUATE THE FACILITY AND CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITHIN 30 MINUTES. UPS'S OUTSIDE RESPONSE CONTACTOR WAS ALSO CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THE PACKAGE AND A VERY SIMILAR COMPANION PACKAGE WERE REMOVED FROM THE FACILITY AND EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO WORK AT 21:35. ANALYSIS OF BATTERIES INVOLVED SHOWED SOME CRACKING OF THE END OF AT LEAST ONE OF THE UNITS IN THE PACKAGE AND NO PROTECTION FOR BATTERY TERMINALS. HOWEVER, THE BATTERIES MAY HAVE HAD EQUIVALENT LITHIUM CONTENT LOW ENOUGH TO BE UNREGULATED IN GROUND TRANSPORTATION

column168: 11/19/12: At approximately 2140 hours, RCO of FC24 walking past tank car TILX 193253, load, Petroleum Crude Oil, located on #1 Recieving in Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, leaking product in multiple steady streams originating from the bottom outlet.  CR Trainmaster L. Jones contacted CR Risk Manager A. Richter.    Further inspection by Mr. Richter and S. Gould, Hepaco-React (CR emergency response contractor) noted the bottom outlet valve for TILX 193253 was fully opened and leaking product originating from the bottom outlet valve's operating stem packing area.  Valve closed at time of inspection, stopping the release of product.  Further inspection found the product was leaking past the bottom outlet valve operating stem packing due to 2 loose packing nuts.  Packing nuts were secured and car forward to original destination.    Further inspection at consignee during and after unloading was performed found no further exceptions.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Driver unloading cargo tank into portable totes.  Output oriface of tractor PTO-driven pump required 3" to 2" reducer to accomodate 2" delivery hose. Driver selected reducer with integral bleeder valve.  Bleeder valve was not necessary for this application, and driver failed to check condition (open/closed) of bleeder prior to unloading.  As unloading progressed, product slowly escaped from open bleeder valve in reducer and pooled under pump.  Driver and attendant noticed spill, shut down unloading and isolated both tanks.  Spill was cleaned up with minimal effort, and unloading resumed without further incident.
column169: Driver retrained on selection of proper equipment for application and instructed on situational awareness while unloading.

column168: A BNSF train operating on main track derailed 23 railcars. The cause of the derailment was a broken rail. Entrained tank car NATX 400756 derailed and came to rest in an upside-down position with its valve housing partially buried in the ground. NATX 400756's tank jacketing sustained a 2-3 foot long by 8 inch wide gouge above the B-end body bolster from contact with another derailed railcar. Contents within NATX 400756 was slowly leaking from the tank from under the damaged jacket area. Air monitoring was established and continued throughout the entire event. An explosive charge was placed upon NATX 400756 and detonated to successfully vent and burn the remaining commodity within NATX 400756. This controlled burn ended by 1430 hrs. CST, 11/05/2012. The evacuation was lifted at 1200 hrs. CST, 11/05/2012.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A FRA Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car SHPX 208181 with product leaking around its bottom outlet cap (BOC). BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected SHPX 208181 and observed product surrounding the exposed threads above the BOC. Further inspection revealed that the bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) was slightly open. The BOV's operating set screw stop was out of adjustment which prevented the valve's operating handle to move the valve to the fully closed position.  Responders adjusted the set screw and moved the operating handle to the fully closed position.  Afterwards, the BOC was removed to inspect the BOC gasket which was found compressed and cut, thus not providing a good seal. The faulty BOC gasket was replaced. The BOC was reapplied and tool tightened. All wet product was wiped and no further commodity seepage was observed. Response was concluded by 1315 hrs. PST, 11/06/2012. No ground impact from spillage was reported. All intact shipper seals removed were replaced by BNSF seals.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: FRA and CAPUC Railroad Safety Inspectors inspecting railcars in the railyard reported entrained tank car UTLX 952337 on a scheduled outbound BNSF train was emanating product odor (vapors) with no liquid release reported. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspection of UTLX 952337 revealed the B-end liquid line valve was partially open and it closure plug was not tool tight. The responders closed the liquid valve and removed the plug for thread cleaning. After the plug threads were cleaned and new thread sealant tape applied, the plug was reinserted and properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no further odor/vapors were detectable. Intact shipper seals were replaced by BNSF seals. Response was concluded by 1155 hrs. PST, 11/07/2012.

column168: FRA and CAPUC Railroad Safety Inspectors inspecting railcars in the railyard reported entrained tank car GATX 2542 on a scheduled outbound BNSF train had one of six manway securement bolts loose and out of position. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders' inspection of GATX 2542's manway securement also revealed a strong product odor emanating from the manway closure. The manway securement bolts were loosened to inspect the manway gasket condition. The manway gasket applied was found compressed and cracked, thus not providing a good seal. The responders applied a new suitable manway gasket and properly secured all manway securement bolts. Afterwards, no further product odor/vapors were detected. Intact shipper seal CSE 797664 at the manway closure was replaced by BNSF seal 06157491. Response was concluded by 1215 hrs. PST, 11/07/2012.

column168: I was contacted of a LPG release in the Roseville Ca. Rail Yard from the MBLX34290. I requested Roseville Fire Hazmat team be notified and respond. Upon the arrival of Roseville Fire they located the MBLX34290 and monitored with a 4 gas monitoring device. Roseville Fire climbed on the tank car and inspected all the valves and fittings under the protective housing. During their inspection they located the liquid valve on the B end of the tank car to be open and the plug of the same valve to be loose (less than tool tight). Roseville Fire closed the Valve a half turn and then removed the plug completely, placing 4 wraps of teflon tape around the threads of the plug and then replacing it on the liquid valve and securing it properly. They then continued to monitor and concluded that there was no longer a leak.   I arrived at approximately 1300 hours on 11/09/2012 and conducted another inspection of the MBLX34290 and concluded it was secure and no leak occurring.
column169: I recommend that Exxon Mobil in Torrance Ca be visited and loading procedures be evaluated, this is the second incident with them with in 17 days.  I recommend that the visit be conducted by the AAR and loading procedures be observed.

column168: Forklift damage to a steel drum during Import storage caused pin hole leak. Less that 2 onces of class 9 material. The hazmat had a strong unpleasent odor. The emergency response tel number / service was not working properly and not able to be contacted to obtain MDSD or other emergency hazmat response information , such as inhaladtion dangers (  if any ) .   Due to lack of hazmat emergecny response information and the strong unpleasent odor the warehouse was evacuated for about 30 minutes. A hazamat company was contacted for cleanup, however the Chicago Fire Department stored the damaged hazmat drum in a salvage drum before the hazmat team arrived.   The hazmat company cleaned up the small amount of spillage ( less than 2 onces )12Nov, which was stored in a remote location away from staff. Hazmat company disposed of this waste.   Emergency response information line was contacted 3 times at the time of the incident without being reached- caller was put on hold for several minutes to get an English speaker but the caller did not understand he was being put on hold as the emergency response staff only spoke French, so the caller hung up each time after being put on hold for several minutes.   The next morning the emergency response number was reached after waiting several minutes, emergency information was not readily available, was provided in about 90 minutes due phone connections of their system and being sent to the incorrect email address due to typo of the emergency response provider.

column168: On 11/15/2012 1730 hrs, I was advised that tank car# CPCX 205032 was observed leaking from the bottom outlet cap.  Car was initially in the "Rip track" building for a five (5) year airbrake test, when it was noted to be leaking.  Car was subsequently isolated outside on track BNR3 do to the nature of the product and a bucket placed under the bottom outlet valve to capture any product.  Upon arrival, I noted the bottom outlet cap was loose and wrenched tighten same and suspected that gasket may be defective. I left the bucket in place in the event of further leakage.  I subsequently  climbed car to open manway to see how much product was remaining in car, as car was being shipped residual  last contained ,Hydrocarbons Liquid N.O.S. I observed the manway bolts loose or off. I opened manway and noted that ball valve was closed and approximately 20-30- US gallons of product remaining I closed manway and tightened all bolts.  Contact was made to SWS Environmental Company for response of gasket replacement on bottom outlet cap. On 11/16/2012, Dave Estep, of SWS arrived on scene and removed bottom outlet cap and noted gasket exceptionally y worn (Figure 1).  Gasket was subsequently replaced with new "Viton" gasket.  Additionally I noted the absence of seals on the following:   Manway, applied IHBRR 164900  Bottom outlet valve, applied IHBRR 164851  Bottom outlet cap, applied IHBRR 164899  Valve Box on top of car was sealed with CPC 270640.  "Chemtrec" was contacted on 11/15/2012 for assistance with notifying shipper/consignee to obtain MSDS information which was supplied.  Chevron Phillips was advised to inspect car for suspected product contamination of residual as manway was not secure. Chevron Phillips advised that car would be flagged. Car was released for movement to destination.
column169: Inspection of bottom outlet gasket for signs of wear, do to frequency of opening and closing of bottom outlet plug which may cause wear on cap. Better inspection of manway and other devices for closure prior to shipment.

column168: Driver obtained his paperwork and walked to the truck, opened the door and put his paperwork into the side pouch. The driver then entered the truck and drove off; crossed over a containment barrier then he heard/felt something that caused him to look at his side view mirror. He saw product coming from the trailer. The hose had been torn free of the loading rack. He stopped and backed up into containment area. A second driver, Rondall Flasket, was behind this unit and saw what had happen. He got out of his truck and shut the internal valve thus stopping the flow of product. No one injured, No fatalities, No evacuations. Spill cleaned by Total personnel 3-hour spill duration. Repairs made to loading station on-going.

column168: Entrained tank car TILX 318680 was reported leaking product from its manway closure during its arrival in the railyard on an inbound BNSF train. Movement was stopped and no additional product release was observed when TILX 318680 remained motionless. Contract responders inspected TILX 318680 finding the applied manway gasket was out of position and cut. The responders removed the damaged manway gasket and installed a new manway nozzle gasket. The manway lid was closed and properly resecured. All spillage around the manway nozzle base and on the side shell evaporated. No ground impact from spillage was noted. The intact shipper seal (numbered 007328) was replaced by seal numbered 846814.

column168: A BNSF mechanical inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car TILX 198362 leaking commodity from its manway closure. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected TILX 198362 and reported finding all six manway securement bolts tool tight. The contractor wrapped absorbent pads around the leaking area in order to contain it and reported that a mechanical fix would most likely be needed.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: At approximately 7:40 P.M. on Friday November 16, 2012, KCS employees reported an ammonia smell emanating from a group of cars in the Beaumont Yard in Beaumont, TX.  Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.    At approxiamtely 9:15 P.M. repsonders arrived and began investigating source of possible ammonia leak. Upon further investigation, two suspected cars were cleared leaving only tank car TELX 556 left (a tank car containing Methyl Mercaptan not ammonia). After a leak detection test was performed using a snoop solution, it was discovered that a small leaked had occurred at the mounting bolts of the pressure relief device (PRD) of the tank car TELX 556. After the responders tried to tighten mounting bolts of PRD to no avail, a Midland capping kit was utilized to contain/stop the leak from the mounting bolts.    After successful installation of Midland kit, per shipper direction, the tank car was immediately switch move back to origin (per 174.50), which is located closely adjacent to the subject yard.     *No injuries were reported.    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable.     For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: Truck driver was delivering nitric acid to the consignees above ground tank by way of pressurizing the cargo tank with a maximum of 20 PSIG of air pressure. The customers’ air supply is regulated to 20 PSIG. The driver had a 3 inch to 2 inch reducer connected to the cargo tanks 3 inch outlet. One 2 inch chemical hose approximately 18 feet in length was connected from the 3-2 reducer fitting to the consignee’s 2 inch receiving line. All connections were camlock type.  It appears the driver disconnect the 2 inch delivery hose at the 3-2 reducer before all product was transferred from the cargo tank to the receiving tank. A plant worker observed product blowing from the rear of the trailer and the driver washing down with a water hose. He immediately radioed for help from others in the plant and assisted the driver to wash down with water. Other workers arriver with the proper PPE and took over assisting the driver to decontaminate. The driver was transported by ambulance and then helicopter to a burn center in Lubbock, TX.   We have not been able to get a statement from the driver who is undergoing medical treatment for chemical burns.   All released material was captured on the concrete drive and spill containment area. Plant personnel treated the material and performed all cleanup activities.
column169: Best practice for receiving dangerous cargo is for the receiver to handle all off loading activities. We see this with other customers where we transport this same type cargo. This customer modified their procedures to require a plant person to be in attendance at the time the driver believes the transfer of product has been completed. The plant person has to be in attendance at all times the drivers is preparing for delivery and when closing valves and disconnecting delivery hoses.

column168: The semi was passing a farm tractor.  When the semi and half of the tank was past the farm tractor, the tractor driver turned left and hit the side of the tank.  The farmer was trying to turn into a field approach.    The farm tractor forced the semi and tank off the road and into a ditch.  The tank separated from the semi and rolled over several times.  The semi then went into the ditch and rolled over.      The piping on the discharge side of the pump was torn off and a gasket inside the internal vavle ripped and stuck inside the valve preventing it from closing completely.  Anhydrous released and blew toward the semi where the driver was unconscious.    A water fog was sprayed onto the leaking anhydrous but the cold weather made the release slow until it was barely noticable allowing responders to approach the tank and install a valve on the pump discharg to eliminate the release.
column169: The addition of a manual valve upstream from the pump would have stopped this release.  This would add a back up shut off incase the internal valve failed.

column168: Tank car GATX 60771 was reported leaking and venting commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard. A BNSF crew operating locomotives that were moving on an adjacent track in the yard reported releasing commodity sprayed onto their locomotives with no contact to the crew inside the locomotive cab. These locomotives were taken to the roundhouse area for later decontamination. BNSF and contract responders inspected the cordoned-off GATX 60771. Responders reported that the vapor/air valve was disconnected at the valve's base pipe flange connection and hanging to one side. All four flange stud nuts were missing along with one stud bolt.  Responders correctly repositioned the valve and applied replacement stainless steel bolts and bolt stud nuts. The bolt stud nuts were tool tightened, thus properly securing the valve at its flange connection. Spillage on GATX 60771 and a small area of ground impact were neutralized with a sodium bicarbonate solution. The impacted BNSF locomotives were rinsed with the same neutralizing solution.  GATX 60771 is awaiting an OTMA for further movement in rail transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Intermodal container NYKU 841712 staged in the intermodal facility's lot awaiting further transport to dock for export to China was reported leaking an unknown liquid by its assigned outbound truck driver. NYKU 841712 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area for inspection. Contract responders inspecting NYKU 841712 reported finding one 55 gallon steel drum (UN Spec 1A1/Y1.6/250/USA/M4712/12) had leaked product from a two inch abrasion cut at this drum's upper rolling hoop from contact with an adjacent drum. Only one strip of Ty-Guard at the load's rear was used to secure the drums which was deemed insufficient for 80 drums in this 40 foot container. The drums rotated and shifted inside NYKU 841712. The leaking drum was placed into an overpack drum. Seven other drums were noted with damage but did not leak. A total of eight drums were earmarked for beneficial recycling. The remaining 72 drums were returned inside the cleaned NYKU 841712 properly secured for continued transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper follows recommended blocking and bracing patterns to prevent lateral and longitudinal movements for hazardous material non-bulk shipments.

column168: The driver reported that after pulling into the consignee's yard, he saw product dripping down the side of the cargo tank.  The rear washout cap was missing.  He wasn't sure when he lost it but he said the road in front of the plant was rough and may have jarred it off.  When asked if he left a trail coming into the yard, he said no.  he just saw product when he stopped in the yard possibly from the surge.  Driver estimates three gallons spilled and he used spill pads to wipe it up.  He obtained another washout cap to secure the trailer.
column169: If the driver had secured the washout cap properly, it would not have jarred loose.  Driver went through remedial training on the proper procedure to follow when securing the washout cap including checking for cross-threading.  The incident also will result in the loss of his quarterly bonus.

column168: A DOT/FRA Inspector during a routine inspection at the intermodal facility observed and reported tank container DCIU 742089 with a slow periodic commodity drip at the container's bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. DCIU 742089 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area for further inspection and securement by contract responders. The responders reported the closed BOV was dripping from its base flange connection. All four flange stud nuts were not tool tight. The flange stud nuts were tool tightened approximately one full turn each and the dripping at the flange connection stopped. Also, the bottom outlet valve's closure cap (BOC) or 'dust cap' was found only hand tight. The BOC was removed and Teflon tape applied to its threaded area. The BOC was then reapplied and tool tightened after all liquid found near the outlet's orifice was wiped.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GATX 22267 was reported dripping liquid from its bottom outlet area while in the railyard. Absorbent material was placed under GATX 22267 and it was cordoned-off in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting GATX 22267 found the top operated bottom outlet valve's (TOBOV) operating rod in a slightly open position and it was moved to its closed position and secured. The residue commodity drips from the bottom outlet's closure cap (BOC) ebbed. The BOC was found not tool tight. The responders tool tightened the BOC thus ending all liquid drips by 2015 hrs. CST, 11/24/2012. Observed spillage at the bottom outlet was wiped and no ground impact from residual commodity drips was observed.

column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE MATERIAL, UN3082, WASTE ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, N.O.S., 9, PGIII, (F006) AT ROLLS-ROYCE (GENERATOR) LOCATED AT 2355 SOUTH TIBBS AVENUE, INDIANAPOLIS, IN ON NOVEMBER 16, 2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 P.M.. IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR TO VAC THE MATERIAL ONTO THE TANKER 11-26. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS DONE LOADING THE MATERIAL IS ACTIVATED THE VAC TO CLEAN OUT THE LINES. ONCE THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THE LINES WERE EMPTIED HE CLOSED THE INLET AND PROCEEDED TO CHECK THE BACK DOME TO ENSURE THAT IT WAS CLOSED PROPERLY AND SECURELY. THE DRIVER THEN CHECKED THE CENTER DOME AND THEN THE FRONT DOME TO ENSURE THAT BOTH WERE CLOSED PROPERLY AND SECURELY. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER ALL FASTENERS WERE CHECKED AND EEMED TIGHT. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO LEAVE THE GENERATOR SITE AND TRAVEL TO HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (HERITAGE) LOCATED AT 7901 WEST MORRIS STREET, INDIANAPOLIS, IN. THE ROUTE TAKEN BY THE DRIVER IS APPROXIMATELY 7 MILES FROM THE GENERATOR TO HERITAGE. DURING THE TRIP TO HERITAGE THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED NUMBEROUS STOPS AND DID NOT SEE ANY MATERIAL BEING RELEASED FROM THE TANKER. ONCE THE DRIVER TURNED ONTO MILE ROAD, THE ENTRANCE TO THE BUSINESS PARK WHERE HERITAGE TRANSPORT IS LOCATED AND THE ROUTE TO THE ENTRANCE TO HERITAGE, HE CAM TO THE STOP SIGN AT RESEARCH WAY. IT WAS AT THIS STOP WHERE THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE MATERIAL COMING OUT FROM THE FRONT DOME. APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANKER ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE MATERIAL COVERED AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 25' X 10' OF THE ROAD. THE MATERIAL WAS QUICKLY CONTAINED AND THE CLEAN UP PROCESS BEGAN IMMEDIATELY BY HERITAGE PERSONNEL. ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO THE AFFECTED AREA, SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN 2-55 GALLON DRUMS TO BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE ROUTE THAT THE DRIVER TOOK FROM THE GENERATOR TO THE SITE OF THE SPILL WAS RETRACED AND DETERMINED THAT NO OTHER MATERIALS WERE RELEASED FROM THE TANKER.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS HEADED NORTH BOUND ON 1-95, IN A BOX VAN, WHEN HIS REAR RIGHT TIRE BLEW CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL, SWERVE AND FLIP UPSIDE DOWN OVER THE GUARDRAIL ONTO THE SOUTHBOUND LANE. THE DRIVER WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL BUT WAS LATER RELEASED WITH NO INJURIES. THE VAN WAS CARRYING LEAD ACID BATTERIES, UN 2794. THE BATTERIES WERE THROWN ABOUT INSIDE THE VAN DURING THE TURNOVER. THE FLORIDA DEP ESTIMATED ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF BATTERY ELECTROLYTE WAS SPILLED ALONGSIDE OF THE ROAD AND ON THE ROAD. EAST PENN CONTACTED A TOWING SERVICE TO UPRIGHT THE VAN AND HAUL AWAY ONCE THE THERE WAS NO MORE SIGN OF LEAKING. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL ALONGSIDE OF THE ROAD AND TO CLEAN OUT THE VAN OF THE LEAD ACID BATTERIES. THEY CLEANED UP THE ROAD AND NEUTRALIZED THE SOIL THAT WAS IMPACTED. THE FLORIDA DEP WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CLEANUP DONE BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR. THE VAN WAS PARKED IN THE TOWING FACILITIES PARKING LOT AND COVERED WITH PLASTIC TO PREVENT ANY RAIN FROM GOING INSIDE THE VAN CAUSING LEAKAGE WHILE WAITING FOR CLEANUP. THE BATTERIES INSIDE THE VAN WERE CLEANED OUT BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR AND EAST PENN A COUPLE DAYS LATER. LIBERAL AMOUNTS OF ABSORBENT; NEUTRALIZING COMPOUND WAS USED THROUGHOUT THE CLEANUP PROCESS. THE BATTERIES WERE PUT INTO PLASTIC BAGS ALONG WITH THE NEUTRALIZING COMPOUND AND RE-SKIDDED WITH CARDBOARD LAYERS IN BETWEEN AND STRETCH WRAPPED. ABSORBENT PADS WERE ALSO APPLIED BETWEEN CARDBOARD ON ALL SIDES UNDER, BETWEEN AND ON TOP OF ALL THE PALLETIZED BATTERIES AS EXTRA PRECAUTION. THE BATTERIES DID COME BACK TO EAST PENN, LYON STATION, PA FOR RECYCLING AT OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER. THE VAN HAS BEEN DECLARED TOTALED BY THE INSURANCE AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS SCRAP METAL.
column169: EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO (AMERICAN BATTERY) BELIEVES THAT NO ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON THE USE OF BETTER PACKAGING IS REQUIRED IN REGARDS TO THE ABOVE MENTIONED INCIDENT. PACKAGING GUIDELINES ARE FOLLOWED - CFR 49 173.159(A) & 173.159(E).

column168: On November 25, 2012, at 21:47 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Willard Terminal, Willard, Ohio noticed wetness on the side of GATX 47182 a loaded tank car of UN1814, Potassium Hydroxide. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Ashta Chemicals Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2012-1125-00041. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Willard Terminal and found the one hundred sixty five (165) pound rupture disc to have been ruptured. Shipper representative, John Bradek, was notified of the concern and corrective action. The release was secured by replacing the disc and GATX 47182 was released for disposition.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100  Cause code:441

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While unloading, leak was discovered coming from freight inside the trailer. Apparently, industrial size batteries were loaded onto pallets, which could not sustain their weight. This resulted in the batteries falling from the pallet, which caused the release of approximately 5 gallons of sulfuric acid. Roadrunner Transportation Services personnel applied saw dust to contain the free product inside the trailer, and on the concrete surface beneath trailer. Patriot Environmental of Long Beach, California was dispatched to perform cleanup. Upon arrival on site, Patriot Environmental off loaded the trailer, repalletized and shrink wrapped the batteries, and neutralized the free product. Waste was containerized into a recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. Trailer was cleaned, and freight was reloaded to be sent on to its destination. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: DN1105/consists of one fibreboard box which contains 29 cans of foam shaving cream, shipped by Karen Grimord at Landstuhl Hospital Care Project, in Stafford VA. Each metal aerosol can contains a net quantity of 7oz (200ml) of shaving foam. Each metal can is marked with Flammable Gas hazard label. The mail shipment originated in New York (JFKIA) and was accepted by Emirates from the United States Post Office as a mail consignment under a military AV-7 document number USB2MEW00268, on 11/05/2012. The package was then transported onflight EK202 - 11/05/2012, from JFK International Airport to Dubai International Airport. The shipment was packaged in a way that prevented the accepting staff from verifying its contents without having to open the package first. Contents were discovered during a routine x-ray screening of transit mail by the Dubai Police.  After the Dubai Police opened the mail parcel, it was physically confirmed that the internal contents were shaving cream cans, classified as UN1950, class 2.1 (Aerosols, Flammable).  External packaging did not contain any hazard labels or markings.  The shipment is currently being held in Dubai, until shipper appoints an agent to perform proper packaging, markings, labeling and documentation.  Only after all IATA/ICAO and FAA/DOT requirements have been met, will the shipment be moved to its final destination of Doha, Qatar.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS AM, ON NOVEMBER 04, 2012, OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE I-5 WITH A SEMI TRACTOR TRAILER & PUP TRAILER LOADED WITH 9000 GALLONS OF AVIATION LOW LEAD (LL). THE SIMI TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 6000 GALLONS OF AV100LL AND THE PUP TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 3000 GALLONS OF AV100LL. APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE NORTH OF THE EXIT 148B TO SR18 OUR DRIVER CAME UPON AN ACCIDENT SCENE WHEREBY A MOTORIST IN VEHICLE #1 HAD LOST CONTROL, STRUCK A GUARDRAIL, ENDING UP IN THE #1 RIGHT LANE OF I-5. IT HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED AND IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AS TO HOW LONG VEHICLE #1 WAS BLOCKING THE LANE. DUE TO THE VIOLENT COLLISION VEHICLE #1 HAD WITH GUARDRAIL THE BATTERY WAS KNOCKED OUT OF THE VEHICLE TAKING OUT THE LIGHTS. VEHICLE #1 WAS A BLACK IN COLOR, THE NIGHT WAS RAINING WITH NO MOON OR STREET LIGHTS TO WARN DRIVERS OF THE BLOCKING VEHICLE. VEHICLES #1 HAD FOUR OCCUPANTS WHO HAD ABANDON THE VEHICLE AND WERE STANDING ON THE SIDE OF THE FREEWAY WHEN THE COLLISION OCCURRED. SHORTLY AFTER THE DRIVER AND THE THREE OCCUPANTS LEFT THE WRECKED VEHICLE IN THE #1 LANE OF TRAVEL, ANOTHER VEHICLE, VEHICLE #2, DRIVING SOUTHBOUND WITH THREE FEMALE OCCUPANTS, STRUCK VEHICLE #1 PUSHING IT INTO THE #2 LANE, OUR VEHICLE'S LANE OF TRAVEL. ACCORDING TO THE WASHINGTON STATE PATROL PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION THEY BELIEVE OUR TRUCK, VEHICLE #3, WAS IN THE #2 SOUTHBOUND LANE WHEN HE CAME UPON VEHICLE #1 BLOCKING THE #2 LANE. DUE TO IT BEING A DARK, RAINING NIGHT AND VEHICLE #1 BEING A SOLID BLACK COLOR WITH NO LIGHTS BELENDING IN WITH THE NIGHT, OUR DRIVER FAILED TO SEE THE WRECKAGE UNTIL HE WAS RIGHT UPON IT, STRIKING VEHICLE #1 WHICH CAUSED OUR DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF HIS TRUCK, DRIVE OFF THE FREEWAY INTO A VERY HIGH RETAINING WALL, TURNING OVER, CATCHING FIRE, KILLING OUR DRIVER. THIS ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AS A CRIME SCENE. THE ABOVE STATEMENT IS FROM CONVERSATIONS WITH INVESTIGATING OFFICERS. OPERATOR OF VEHICLE #1 WAS ARRESTED AND TAKEN TO JAIL ON DUI AND VEHICULAR HOMICIDE. A COLLISION REPORT NUMBER WAS NOT GIVEN AT THE SCENE BY WSP. PLEASE NOTE THAT THE PULL TRAILER #2 WAS LAST INSPECTED 03/30/2012. ALSO BOTH THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE WASHINGTON STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED. BUT THE PAPER WITH THE REPORT NUMBERS ON IT WAS LOST AT THE SCENE.
column169: SAFETY MEETINGS WERE HELD AT ALL TERMINALS DESCRIBING THE INCIDENT AND HOW TO PREVENT IT. A "HOT TOPICS" HANDOUT WILL BE GIVEN TO ALL DRIVERS AND WILL BE POSTED AT EACH LOCATION. WE ARE SCHEDULING DEFENSIVE DRIVING SAFETY MEETING EVEN THOUGH WE HAD DEFENSIVE DRIVING CLASSES 5 MONTHS AGO. WE ARE RE-ROUTING OUR TRUCKS TO TRY AND AVOID THE RISKIER AREA OF FREEWAYS DURING BAR CLOSING TIMES.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While preparing the container for shipment, a small leak was discovered coming from the container.  The free liquid impacted asphalt and quickly evaporated.  United States Environmental Services, LLC of New Orleans, LA was dispatched to inspect the container and perform the necessary cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, one (1) damaged 55-gallon drum was discovered.  Apparently the drum was damaged during loading, resulting in a very small hole.  United States Environmental Services, LLC over-packed the leaking drum and placed onto the container for delivery.  An estimated 0.5 gallon of free product was released and evaporated.  No cleanup was required.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental and appears to be the result of damage by the shipper during loading, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: In process of pumping product from an ISO Container onto our MC 307 trailer, the driver failed to open the external valve on the trailer.  This caused pressure to build up and rupture the 3-inch loading hose. The external valves on the ISO Container were closed immediately which stopped flow of product.  Operators was standing adjacent to valve when hose ruptured. Approximately 15 gals. of product spilled on concrete and small portion ran off onto gravel area.  Booms and absorbent pads were in place and absorbed most of the product, portion that ran off concrete was dug up and disposed of.
column169: Additional training and supervision for the driver . And additional safety check to insure bypass on pump is operative prior to pumping on a load .

column168: As the driver was traveling down a narrow road one of the front tires caught the edge of the roadway and the truck started into the trees then pulled to the side.  The driver states that he did not over correct.  The tire was just too far over.  The vehicle rolled.  The driver and other personnel found a small leak at the pipe and reel assembly shut off valve.  The release was minimal approximately one pint of vapor.  The release was stopped immediately by tightening the valve.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: DOCK PERSONNEL NOTICED A TOTE OF MINERAL SPIRITS LEAKING ON THE DOCK AT THE START OF THE DAILY SHIFT. A HAZMAT CREW WAS CALLED INTO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TOTE. THE HAZMAT CREW IDENTIFIED LOW LOWER VALVE ON THE TOTE HAD BEEN CRACKED OPEN. THE HAZMAT CREW SHUT THE VALVE WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. A CUP WAS PLACED OVER THE OUTLET AND ZIP TIES WERE ATTACHED TO THE VALVE HANDLE AND THE CAP TO ENSURE THE VALVE HANDLE WOULD NOT RE-OPEN DURING TRANSPORTATION.
column169: A POSSIBLE SUGGESTION WOULD BE FOR THE MANUFACTURE OF THE PRODUCT TO ENSURE THE VALVES ARE PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURED SO THEY WILL NOT OPEN AFTER FILLING.

column168: On Tuesday November 20, 2012 Orica driver, Billy Ralph Holmes was involved in a single vehicle accident on I-85 North near Thomasville, North Carolina while en route to a customer location, driving MMU unit 421. At approximately 6:19AM Mr. Holmes failed to maintain control of the MMU after the front driver’s side steer tire blew out, causing the vehicle to leave the road and roll over multiple times; coming to rest on its top. The MMU was loaded with approximately 16,000 LBS of Oxidizer emulsion (UN3139), 7,000 LBS of Ammonium Nitrate (UN1942), a quantity of 100 - 1.4 B Detonators (UN0361) and a quantity of 100 - 1.1D Boosters (UN0042).  Approximately 1,500 LBS of ammonium nitrate prill was spilled to the ground, no emulsion was lost from the tank.  Both detonators and boosters remained secured in the onboard IME-22 magazines, undamaged.  A small amount of diesel fuel, engine oil and antifreeze leaked from the vehicle.  Hepaco, LLC, an Orica third party environmental response company, cleaned the incident scene. The cleanup and disposal process was completed to state and federal standards.    The manway covers on the Ammonium Nitrate Bin were ripped off during the rollover and the bin was upside down after coming to rest.    The Ammonium Nitrate exited from the bin through the then uncovered manway.    The cargo tank containing Oxidizer emulsion did not fail nor did the 2 IME-22 containers holding the detonators and boosters.
column169: The cause of the incident is being investigated by a 3rd party accident reconstruction firm.    The packages held containment with the exception of the manway cover on the Ammonium Nitrate bin being ripped off after rolling over repeatedly.    If the investigation indicates further training is required - it will be provided to drivers.

column168: Tank car SHQX 5297 was reported by a switch crew emanating a commodity odor in the railyard. SHQX 5297 was cordoned-off and switching operations in the railyard were suspended. BNSF and contract responders inspected SHQX 5297 and reported finding the B-end liquid valve partially open with its closure plug loose. Responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug ending the commodity release by 0530 hrs. PST, 11/26/2012. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. SHQX 5297's valve housing cover was resealed with seal numbered 300526. Switching operations in the railyard were resumed by 0645 hrs. PST, 11/26/2012.

column168: November 30, 2012: At approximately 7:05am, CR train FC42-30 was pulling south with 68 loads and 14 empties, total 9321 tons, when cars 6-12 in consist derailed while crossing CR's Paulsboro Moveable Bridge, M.P. 13.07 on the Pennsgrove Secondary.     The 10th car (5th in derailment), OCPX 80234, load, Vinyl Chloride, was punctured on the car's right side, about middle of the tank by "A" end coupler and end sill of OCPX 80323 .  Hole measured approximately 4' x 4'. Tank car was reportedly shipping 23,184 gallons of product, estimating loss at time of incident approximately 20,000 gallons.  Remainder of product was transferred.  Car has been cleaned and purged on site.    All tank cars involved will be maintained (after all are cleaned and purged) at Conrail's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, by order of the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), for their future inspections/investigations.    Also involved in derailment:    ECUX 881493 (6th car in consist and 1st car in derailment), loaded hopper Plastic Pellets, derailed on side.  Product leaking from all bottom hatches and one top hatch.  Product vaccumed and transferred;   SGLR 6298 (7th car in consist and 2nd car in derailment), loaded flat car of Lumber, derailed on its side.  All lumber was transferred during rerailing process;  UTLLX 207398 (8th car in consist and 3rd car in derailment), loaded tank car Alcohol, NOS, 111A100W1 (seperate .5800 submitted);  OCPX 80323 (9th car in consist and 4th car in derailment), loaded tank car Vinyl Chloride Stabalized (seperate .5800 submitted);  OCPX 80234 (10th car in consist and 5th car in derailment; and subject of this report);  UTLX 98097 (11th car in consist and 6th car in derailment), loaded tank car Vinyl Chloride Stabalized (seperate .5800 submitted);  UTLX 98041 (12th car in consist and 7th car in derailment), loaded tank car Vinyl Chloride Stabalized (seperate .5800 submitted).
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The incident took place at the third delivery stop of the morning of 11/26/12. The spilled material was one of two 275 gallon totes of Moor Floc 5401. The proper shipping name of this material is UN3264, Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, NOS (contains Aluminum Sulfate). The product was intended for delivery to the second delivery address at 2100 Burlingame Avenue, SW, Grand Rapids, MI 49509, but there were a number of trucks lined up for deliveries at the loading dock there, with an estimated 1 hour wait time, so the driver decided to go to the third delivery stop at the 150 Cottage Grove, SW Grand Rapids, MI 49507 location, and return to make the delivery to the 2100 Burlingame customer later.    At the 150 Cottage Grove location, the driver needed to unload the tote of Moor Floc 5401 to be able to offload the products needed by the customer at that location.  So the tote involved in the incident was removed from the truck with the use of an electric pallet jack and set aside on the customer's  loading dock.  The products intended for that customer were unloaded.  The incident occurred when the driver was repositioning the tote of Moor Floc 5401 back on the truck with the pallet jack. The bottom valve assembly caught on the corner of the other tote of Moor Floc 5401 in the truck and completely snapped off. The entire contents of the tote emptied off the back of the truck into the storm drain (an 8"x 15' grate spanning the width of the loading dock, connected to the storm sewer system on the customer property).  The driver attempted to replace the valve to stop the flow, but the break was such as to make this impossible.  Incidental skin contact occurred but was promptly washed off, and no injuries to the driver or any other responder occurred.    The customer's environmental manager and other personnel were already in the near vicinity when the spill occurred. The immediate response was to bring out a tank wagon to suck out the first on-property storm sewer retention chamber. (The storm water system at this location included four retention chambers on the customer's property before connection to the City of Grand Rapids storm sewer line located under Cottage Grove Avenue.)  When testing of the pH of the downstream retention chambers showed carryover of the product, the customer's liquid waste contractor was called to arrange for response by their vac truck. At the same time, the National Response Center, the state Pollution Emergency Action System, and local authorities were notified as a precaution. The Grand Rapids Fire Department responded with a number of emergency vehicles. However, all spilled product was recovered from the four storm water retention chambers on customer  property by the tank wagon and vac truck. The storm water chamber at the junction of the customer's line into the city line was opened for inspection and sampling, but was dry, indicating that no spilled product had migrated beyond the facility limits.    The Broadmoor

column168: Driver was traveling on hwy 97 when he lost control of the vehicle and the tractor and trailer both rolled over.  The trailer came to rest on its side with the dome lid facing toward the ground.  The dome lid began to leak around the seal.  The leak was a fairly slow leak until the clean up process began.  The clean up company had to cut a whole in the side of the tanker so they could get access to the acid and then pump it into another trailer.  The leak last for approximately 8 hours.  The acid was contained on the soil on the side of the road.  Berms were made with the soil to keep the acid contained.  Once the trailer was emptied, the acid on the ground was neutralized and then cleaned up using vacuum trucks.  The soil was then remediated to ensure all of the contaminated soil was removed.  Samples of the soil were taken to ensure no contamination remained.  Once the samples confirmed this, clean soil was brought in to replace the contaminated soil.  Arizona Department of Environmental Quality was involved and oversaw the remediation portion of the process.
column169: We have implemented a strict no speeding policy on the highway.  This is a very winding road with no shoulders so there is little tolerance for error.  We have told our drivers by company memo that they are required to travel 10 mph below all posted and recommended speeds on that highway.  We have also sent our safety team out to the highway to have conversations with our drivers and to help enforce the new standard.

column168: AFTER UNLOADING PRODUCT AT THE CONSIGNEE AND RETURNING TO THE QUALITY CARRIERS TERMINAL, OUR DRIVER NOTICED DRY PRODUCT RESIDUE AT THE 3" AIR UNLOADING ASSEMBLY AT THE TOP OF THE CTMV. TERMINAL PERSONNEL ESTIMATED THAT A FEW OUNCES TO A PINT OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE ASSEMBLY, AND IT IS PRESUMED THAT THE LEAK OCCURRED WHEN THE CTMV WAS PRESSURIZED (THROUGH THE AIR UNLOADING ASSEMBLY) DURING UNLOADING. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT PRODUCT RELEASED OR DRIPPED FROM THE EXTERIOR OF THE CTMV. THE RELEASE WAS NOT NOTED AT THE TIME OF UNLOADING, HOWEVER, WE ARE REPORTING THE CONSIGNEE ADDRESS AS THE LOCATION OF THIS INCIDENT.    THE ASSEMBLY WAS INSPECTED, AND THE GASKET AT THE 3" CAP WAS FOUND TO BE DEFECTIVE. SHOP PERSONNEL REPLACED THE ENTIRE 3" AIR UNLOADING ASSEMBLY WITH A NEW GRAND EQUIPMENT MODEL GIR 3ADS.    OUR EVENT 35522.

column168: TRANSPORT TRUCK OWNED BY COBB OIL NEGOTIATED A TURN AT A RATE OF SPEED THAT CAUSED A SLOW SPEED ROLLOVER. THE OUTER SKIN OF THE TRAILER TORE AS WELL AS THE INTERNAL BULK HEADS RESULTING IN A SLOW LEAKAGE. OTTUMWA HAZMAT RESPONSE CUT HOLES INTO THE TANK IN EACH COMPARTMENT ALLOWING PRODUCT (DIESEL) TO BE PUMPED OUT. SPILLING PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED USING SAND BERMS TO PREVENT IT FROM SPREADING. TRUCK WAS PLACED BACK ON IT'S WHEELS AND REMOVED FROM SCENE IN ABOUT 4-5 HRS. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PUMPED INTO CONTAINERS AND CONTAMINATED TOP SOIL WAS REMOVED AND TAKEN TO THE LOCAL LANDFILL FOR REMEDIATION. TOP SOIL WAS REPLACED AND RE-SEEDED WITH MESH PLACED TO REDUCE ERROSION. DNR SIGNED OFF AS WELL AS IOWA DOT.
