column168: Driver was delivered 7500 gallons of diesel to the station.  He overfilled the tank by accident causing a spill of first reported approx. 100 gallons.  The driver immediatly stopped the flow of product and contained the spill with his spill kit. Emergency response (Rolan plant services) was called immediatly to the scene. IDEM was also notified immediately. (report # 32402) Only the asphalt and concrete area was impacted.  No soil or water was impacted.  Rolan Plant services place absorbants to clean the area.  After the absorbants were removed Rolan Plant services pressure washed the area to remove the stain on the concrete.  When the tank charts and gallons were reconciled the inventory and the gallons delivered it was discovered that only 27 gallons were missing from the inventory.  The orignal estimate of 100 gallons was high and only 27 gallons of diesel were unaccounted for.  We recieved a verbal no futher action necessary from Greg Carter with the IDEM.
column169: We continue to educate our drivers on proper unloading procedures.  This driver was retrained by his safety manager.

column168: V1(FLYING J TRANSPORTATION LLC) WAS HEADIND EAST ON STATE HIGHWAY 2021 (BUCKEYE ROAD), WHEN V2(JAMES HELLER IN A 2002 CHEVROLET CAVALIER) WAS HEADING WEST ON BUCKEYE ROAD. V2 WAS TRAVELING IN THE WRONG LANE COMING TOWARDS V1, AN THEN SWERVED OUT OF THAT LANE AND AT THE LAST MOMENT SWERVED INTO THE DRIVER SIDE MIDDLE PORTION OF V1'S TRAILER. THE IMPACT FROM V2 HITTING V1'S TRAILER CAUSED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2,075 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.    V1 CONTACTED THE FLYING J MANAGEMENT TEAM IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, AS WELL AS LOCAL AUTHORITIES. THE FLYING J MANAGEMENT TEAM SENT OUT A VENDOR TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP AND MITIGATION OF ALL FUEL SPILLED AT THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: ALL FLYING J DRIVERS RECEIVE SAFETY TRAINING, WHICH TEACHES THEM TO ALWAYS BE ALERT AND DEFENSIVE WHEN DRIVING. AFTER REVIEWING THE DETAILS OF THE EVENT, IT APPEARS THAT IT WAS NOT A LACK OF DRIVER/AWARENESS THAT LEAD TO THIS TAKING PLACE. FLYING J WILL HOWEVER CONTINUE TO TRAIN OUR DRIVERS IN ALL AREAS OF SAFETY.

column168: THE ILLINOIS VALLEY SUPPLY, LLC TRUCK DRIVEN BY EMPLOYEE TYLER J REICHMANN WAS PULLING TWO 1,000 GALLON NURSE TANKS SIDE BY SIDE TRAVELING EAST ON COUNTRY RD 7, WHEN THE DRIVER FELT THE TRAILER FISHTAILING AND SLOWED HIS SPEED OF ABOUT 30 MPH AND APPLIED THE BRAKES IN RESPONSE. IN THE REVIEW MIRROR, THE DRIVER SAW THE RUNNING GEAR VEER, SLIDE AROUND AND SPIN THE TRUCK INTO THE NORTH DITCH FACING THE WEST. THE REESE HITCH OF THE TRUCK HAS A PITCH PIN CLIP IN IT THAT APPARENTLY CAME OUT AND LET THE TRAILER RECEIVER DISCONNECT FROM THE TRUCK. THIS CAUSED THE NURSE TANKS TO VEER FROM DITCH TO DITCH AND RUN OVER AND TURN OVER AND BREAKING OFF THE VALVES ON ONE OF THE NURSE TANKS, ALLOWING ANYDROUS AMMONIA TO BE RELEASED INTO THE AIR. GREENFIELD FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AT SCENE AT 8.30AM AND STARTED SPRAYING THE CLOUD OF AMMONIA THAT WAS COMING FROM THE NURSE TANK THAT HAD VALVES SHEARED OFF. ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF GARY PENCE SAID THAT HE AND OTHER FIREMEN EVACUATED TWO RESIDENCES FROM THEIR HOMES WITHIN 200 YARDS OF ANYDROUS AMMONIA RELEASE. GREEN COUNTY SHERIFF'S CHIEF DEPUTY CALE HOESMAN ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND WAS MET ASST FIRE CHIEF GARY PENCE WHO ADVISED THE CHIEF DEPUTY OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND WHAT WAS BEING DONE TO CONTROL THE ANYDROUS AMMONIA RELEASE. INSPECTOR STEVE SMOTHERS FROM THE ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 10.35 AM AND MET WITH ASST FIRE CHIEF GARY PENCE AND CHIEF DEPUTY CALE HOESMAN. PENCE & HOESMAN ADVISED INSPECTOR SMOTHERS ON WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND WHAT WAS BEING DONE TO CONTROL THE RELEASE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. CHIEF PENCE SAID ONE NURSE TANK'S PROTECTIVE CAGE AND VALVE WERE KNOCKED OFF RELEASING  ANYDROUS AMMONIA INTO THE AIR AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, UTILIZING SBA UNITS, WAS SPRAYING WATER ON THE NURSE TANK UNTIL THE TANK WAS EMPTY. THE SECOND TANK'S VALVES REMAINED SHUT OFF. WHILE SPRAYING WATER, THE SAFETY HOOK AND CHAIN STILL ATTACHED TO THE TRUCK WAS CUT OFF BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ENABLING THE TRUCK TO BE DRIVEN AWAY A SAFE DISTANCE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTINUED SPRAYING WATER ON THE LEAKING TANK UNTIL IT WAS NO LONGER RELEASING AMMONIA. THE FIRE DPARTMENT HAD CALLED DAVIS TOWING FROM CARLINVILLE WHO THEN REMOVED THE RUNNING GEAR AND TANKS BY WRECKER. THE ROCKBRIDGE-CHESTERFIELD BLACKTOP, ABOUT 1 MILE EAST OF 267 WAS CLOSED 11/2/2012 FROM 8:30 AM AND NOT REOPENED UNTIL 11/9/2012 WHEN CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED. THE AREA ON THE ROAD AND THE AREA ALONGSIDE THE ROAD HAD ANYDROUS AMMONIA SPILLED. A POND OF WATER ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROAD HAD AMMONIA RUN OFF INTO IT. ABOUT 12.00PM, IEPA ARRIVED ON THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AND DIRECT THE CLEANUP.
column169: 1) HAVE HAD EMERGENCY PLAN MANAGEMENT GUIDE WITH HANDI-PLAN AND CONTINUE TO FOLLOW.    2) ANNUAL TRAINING WITH LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS    3) REPLACED ALL "REESE" HITCHES WITH SOLID FLAT-BAR HITCHES ON ALL TOWING VEHICLES.

column168: Driver arrived at Quality Discount Heating Oil to deliver 7,500 gallons of heating oil. He had not been to the location before and was not aware that there were two  heating oil tanks, one 8k, and one 12k. He manually stuck the 8k, but used a 12k  tank chart to determine the ullage (delivery amount tank would accept). He started  dropping the product and, sometime later, heard the product stop flowing. When he  disengaged the delivery hose from the fill, heating oil flowed out of the fill onto  the asphalt driveway and down to a storm sewer entrance. The driver used his spill  kit to dam up the product (later determined to be 7 gallons by the business owner)  and called for assistance. Shipley notified Mountain Research of Altoona, PA and  they responded to the site and completed the cleanup. No product went beyond the  entrance of the storm sewer, but the asphalt lot was old and cracked so PA DEP ordered a site characterization. The site characterization report has not yet been made available.
column169: The delivery account notes have been updated to show both the 8k and 12k tanks.  The delivery driver has a tank chart for both tanks.

column168: ON 11/5/12 DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO UNIVAR IN BORGER, TEXAS. APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES PRIOR TO ARRIVING AT UNIVAR OUR DRIVER WAS CRESTING A HILL ON HWY 207 WHEN A PICKUP TRUCK PULLED OUT FROM A HIDDEN DRIVEWAY. OUR DRIVER HAD TO CONDUCT A HARD BARKE EVENT TO AVOID BROAD SIDING THE PICK UP TRUCK.  THIS EVENT CAUSED THE IBC TOTE TO ALL SHIFT FORWARD APPROXIMATELY 8 TO 10 INCHES. USUALLY THE TOTES ARE BLOCKED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER BY A STACK OF WODDEN PALLETS STACKED ABOUT 46 INCHES HIGH WHICH IS THE HEIGHT OF THE TOTES. THIS WILL PREVENT THE TOTES FROM MOVING FORWARD. HOWEVER ON THIS LOAD IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PALLETS WERE ONLY STACKED AT 24 TO 26 INCHES HIGH. WHEN THE DRIVER HAD TO HARD BRACKE THE SHIFTING TOTES CAUSED THE TOP HALF OF THE TOTE IN FRONT TO FOLD OVER TO THE TOP OF THE PALLETS RUPTURING THE FRONT PALLET JUST ABOVE THE 1/2 WAY POINT ON THE TOTE. THIS CAUSED THE SLOW LEAK OF APPROXIMATELY 127 GALLONS OF BLEACH. DURING THE NEXT 5 MILES TO UNIVAR THE DRIVER DID NOT HAVE ANY IDEA THERE WAS A LEAK. THE PRODUCT PULLED UP IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS WHEN THE DRIVER BEGAN BACKING INTO THE DOCK AT UNIVAR IT WAS DISCOVERED THERE WAS A LEAK. OUR DRIVER AND UNIVAR USED BOOMS TO DIKE UP THE BLEACH AND CALLED IN A VAC TRUCK TO PICK UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. SOME ABSORBENT WAS USED AS WELL TO DIKE UP THE BLEACH TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP. TWO IBC WERE USED TO RETURN PRODUCT TO PETRA ALONG WITH 3 BARRELS USED FOR ABSORBENT AND USED BOOMS.
column169: IT WAS DETERMINED AND DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER THAT A FULL STACK OF WOODEN PALLETS HAS TO BE USED TO PREVENT SHIFTING OF TOTES WHILE IN TRANSIT. LOADERS ARE BEING RETRAINED TO MAKE SURE A FULL STACK OF PALLETS ARE USED FOR BLOCKING. NRC WAS CONTACTED BY UNIVAR. WE HAVE CONDUCTED TAILGATE SAFETY MEETINGS TO RETRAIN DRIVERS TO DOUBLE CHECK FOR PROPER BLOCKING IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THIS IS A FUNCTION THE SHIPPER CARRIERS OUT DUE TO THE FACT DRIVERS ARE NOT PRESENT AT LOADING, HOWEVER DRIVER MUST DOUBLE CHECK THE BLOCKING PRIOR TO DEPARTURE.

column60: Ripped or Torn; Ripped or Torn
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON A FOUR-LANE NON-CONTROLLED ACCESS HIGHWAY WHEN HE SAW A DEER STANDING DIRECTLY IN HIS PATH. ACCORDING TO SUBSEQUENT INTERVIEWS, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO SWERVE RIGHT, IN AN EFFORT TO MISS THE DEER, AND IN DOING SO THE TRUCK PASSENGER SIDE STEER TIRE VEERED OFF THE PAVEMENT AND DROPPED INTO AN VERY LARGE POTHOLE THAT WAS APPROXIMATELY 10 INCHES OR MORE DEEP. THIS SUDDEN AND HARSH IMPACT CAUSED THE DRIVER TO IMMEIDATELY LOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND THE UNIT FLIPPED OVER ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE, SLID APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET, AND STRUCK A TREE WITH THE TANK TRAILER OVERTURN FLASHING. THE IMPACT FROM THE TREE CAUSED A STRUCTURAL FAILURE ON THE DOT-406 TRAILER IN THE REAR NUMBER 5 COMPARTMENT.    THE BREECH OCCURRED NEAR THE MANUFACTURED WELD SEAM. OTHERWISE, THE BARREL ITSELF DID NOT FALL.    I HAVE INCLUDED PHOTO ATTACHMENTS, AND INFORMATION EXTRACTED FROM OUR ON-BOARD COMMUNICATIONS SYSTEM THAT PROVIDES PERTINENT DETAILS OF THE TRUCK'S ACTIVITY PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT. AS REFERENCE, THIS DATA CONFIRMED THE DRIVER DID NOT ACT IN AN ABRUPT OR UNSAFE FASHION, HENCE, HIS TESTIMONY OF THE EVENTS WAS VALIDATED.
column169: WACCAMAW TRANSPORT, THROUGH NUMEROUS SAFETY AND TRAINING PROGRAMS, CONTINUOUSLY EMPHASIZES THAT DRIVERS ARE TO MAINTAIN THEIR LANE IN THE EVENT AN ANIMAL OR OTHER  IMPEDIMENT BECOMES A HIGHWAY OBSTACLES. ALTHOUGH, THIS POINT IS CONSTANTLY STRESSED, FOR SOME INDIVIDUALS, HUMAN INSTINCTS MAY AFFECT THEIR ABILITY TO SUCCESSFULLY DO SO.  ADDITIONALLY, THE TRACTOR IN THIS INSTANCE WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SOPHISTICATED ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEM, HOWEVER, THERE IS NO EXISTING ALTERNATIVE IN THE TRUCKING INDUSTRY THAT COULD HAVE ANTICIPATED A POTHOLE OF SUCH  MAGNITUDE, AND THEREBY, HELPED TO PREVENT THE ROLLOVER.    REGARDING THE PACKAGING, THE DOT 406 SPECIFICATION WORKED QUITE WELL IN THIS SITUATION. AS YOU WILL SEE FROM THE PHOTOS, THE TRAILER SUSTAINED SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE ALL AROUND, AND IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A TOTAL LOSS. FORTUNATELY, THE ONLY PRODUCT LOST WAS FROM THE REAR COMPARTMENT, WHERE THE IMPACT WITH THE TREE OCCURRED.    RECOMMENDATIONS: SINCE THE FAILURE WAS NEAR THE WELD SEAM PERHAPS THICKER MATERIAL IN THIS AREA WOULD PROVIDE ADDED STRENGTH. HOWEVER, THIS CONSIDERATION IS UNDER THE JURISDICTION OF EQUIPMENT MANUFACTURING REGULATIONS.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING EAST ON AL 50. WHILE NEGOTIATING A VERY SHARP CURVE, THE TRUCK CROSSED THE CENTER LINE AND THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT THE TRUCK. DUE TO THE SUDDEN DIRECTION CHANGE OF THE TRUCK BY THE DRIVER, THE LIQUID IT WAS FILLED WITH BEGAN SHIFTING AND CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BECOME TOP-HEAVY AND OVERTURN TO THE RIGHT. THE TRAILER OVERTURNING PULLED THE CAB OF THE TRUCK OVER TO THE RIGHT. ALSO THE TRUCK CAME TO REST, OVERTURNED ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD IN A DITCH.
